net.sf.openrds
Class NodeFactory

java.lang.Object
  net.sf.openrds.NodeFactory
public final class NodeFactory
extends java.lang.Object

This class can be used to help starting a main node and/or a process node, setting up a distributed system. In most cases, applications will need just the helper methods on this class to setup a distributed system, but applications that require more control over the system flow may want to initialize node classes manually.
This class does basically 4 things:

  • Instantiates a Main/Process Node
  • Starts a new registry or connect to a remote registry
  • Starts an http daemon for allowing dynamic class download (if wanted)
  • Register instantiated objects

    startMainNode

    public IMainNode startMainNode()
                        throws java.rmi.RemoteException,
                               java.io.IOException,
                               NodeAlreadyExistsException
    Creates a MainNode able to distribute requisitions over the network to other nodes, and starts a new local registry. The started main node will allow dynamic class downloads.
    Please note that this implementation will use the default values for the registry port and http port, but you can change it if necessary by calling RegistryHandler.getInstance().initialize(registryPort, httpPort) BEFORE starting the main node.

    Returns:
    the newly created and registered node
    Throws:
    java.rmi.RemoteException - if failed to export or register object
    java.io.IOException - if any error prevents the initialization of the registry and/or http daemon.
    NodeAlreadyExistsException - if there is an started MainNode already.
    Since:
    OpenRDS 1.1-beta

    createProcessNode

    public ProcessNode createProcessNode()
                              throws java.io.IOException
    Creates a new process node but does not start it. The client application can start it later, after performing any necessary modification, such as adding node listeners to it.
    Just ensure that RegistryHandler.getInstance().initialize() is called before starting the process node, or it will not be able to connect to the main node.
    This method may use a JNI interface for getting the processor clock and memory amount so be aware that an UnsatisfiedLinkError may be thrown.

    Returns:
    the process node
    Throws:
    java.io.IOException - on any error detecting local IP address
    Since:
    OpenRDS 1.1-beta
    See Also:
    RegistryHandler.initialize(String, int, int), ProcessNode.start()
